Isolated from rotting figs collected March 22, 2017, from Dave Rowell's backyard, Nardoo Crescent, Canberra, ACT, Australia. Derived from single hermaphrodite picked from worms recovered from Baermann Funnel, April 2. Same fig sample as QG2810. From google earth: 35°15'14.95"" S, 149°06'54.27"" E.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from rotting figs collected 4/9/17 along the Mt. Cordeaux trail, Main Range National Park, QLD, Australia. Garmin gps (mark118) 28°02.843'S 152°23.618'E. Baermann funnel yielded enormous numbers of worms 4/12. 10 L4s to a plate; only one was a hermaphrodite, which I picked to found this line. from GPS 118, 4/10/17.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from rotting olives collected 5/17/17 from the garden in front of Holy Smoke, Pemberton, Western Australia. Olives plated 5/22/17; teeming with hermaphrodite Caenorhabditis. One young adult singled 5/23/17. Same bag of olives as QG2823. 34°27'04.00"" S 116°01'58.68"" E, from Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from a ziplock of soil, figs, nuts, and litter collected under the sprawling fig tree at the entrance to Kings Park, Perth, Western Australia, 5/20/2017. Baermann funnel plated 5/24/17, yielding thousands of worms, including huge numbers of male and hermaphrodite Caenorhabditis. This plate was founded by one adult hermaphrodite singled 5/24. Its progeny were all hermaphrodites. Same funnel as QG2828 and QG2829. 31°57'17"" S 115°50'40.5"" E by Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from a ziplock of soil, figs, nuts, and litter collected under the sprawling fig tree at the entrance to Kings Park, Perth, Western Australia, 5/20/2017. Baermann funnel plated 5/24/17, yielding thousands of worms, including huge numbers of male and hermaphrodite Caenorhabditis. This plate was founded by one adult hermaphrodite and one adult male 5/24. Singled herm progeny showed that the isolate is androdioecious. Same funnel as QG2827 and QG2829. 31°57'17"" S 115°50'40.5"" E by Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from mushroom rot (photographed) along the Rainforest Circuit, D'Aguilar NP, Queensland, 5/28/17. Baermann funnel plated 5/30/17; few worms, mostly not Caeno. This line was founded by one YA hermaphrodite, 5/30/17. Same funnel as QG2833. Very approx 27°19'52""S, 152°45'49""E, by Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from a bag of purple berries, mostly dried, collected along the Westside Track, D'Aguilar NP, Queensland, 5/28/17; this sample of berries is from a spot a few hundred feed along the track from the bag that yielded QG2836-7. Baermann funnel plated 5/30; lots of Caeno hermaphrodites. This line was founded by one L4 singled 5/30/17. Same funnel as QG2834. Very approx 27°19'51""S 152°45'33""E by Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from a bag of purple berries, mostly dried, collected along the Westside Track, D'Aguilar NP, Queensland, 5/28/17; this sample of berries is from a spot a few hundred feed along the track from the bag that yielded QG2834-5. Baermann funnel plated 5/30. This line was founded by one L4 singled 6/2/17. Same funnel as QG2836. Very approx 27°19'51""S 152°45'33""E by Google Earth.

Androdioecious Caenorhabditis isolated from sample of litter and small figs, Lamington NP, Queensland, 6/4/17. Baermann funnel plated 6/6/17; diverse worms, lots of Caeno hermaphrodite adults and larvae. One young adult picked 6/6 to found this line. Another founded QG2842. By garmin GPS, 28°14.648' S, 153°12.375' E.
